  In 1993, the economic results of industry were improved; the 
comprehensive industrial enterprise index at and above the 
township level, which was calculated independently, was 110.76; 
the sales rate of industrial products reached 96.9 percent; the 
profit and tax rate of funds was 14.8 percent; the cost-profit 
margin was 6.5 percent; circulating funds turned over 1.86 
times; the value-added rate of industry was 29.2 percent; and 
the overall labor productivity (calculated on the basis of the 
valued added) was 18,175 yuan. Cane sugar is one of the 
economic pillars of our region. In the 1992-93 sugar-pressing 
season, the region's cane sugar output rose, achieving first 
place in the country. Reversing the unmarketable situation in 
the previous year, sugar sold well and the whole industry turned 
deficits into profits and brought about tremendous growth in 
profits and taxes, thus playing an important role in improving 
our region's industrial results. However, some enterprises 
still were plagued by poor economic results and countless 
operational difficulties. 
  The construction industry continued to develop rapidly. In 
1993, the value added by this sector totalled 4.093 billion 
yuan, up 32.1 percent over the previous year. The completed 
floor space of buildings was 2.358 million square meters, up 4.2 
percent; overall labor productivity grew 56.1 percent over the 
previous year; and the quality of buildings also improved. 
  III. Fixed-Asset Investment 
  The pace of constructing a passage to the sea in the 
southwest was accelerated, and greater fixed-asset investment 
was made. In 1993, completed fixed-asset investment was 22.125 
billion yuan, up 56.9 percent over the previous year. The 
investment and the extent of growth in fixed assets last year 
was the largest since the policy of reform and opening up was 
implemented. Of this, the investment of state-owned units was 
17.14 billion yuan, representing an increase of 110 percent; 
that of collective units was 1.756 billion yuan, up 13.0 
percent; and individual investment was 3.255 billion yuan, which 
was more or less the same as the previous year. There were 
3,196 new projects started by state-owned units, 760 fewer than 
the previous year, accounting for 48.8 percent of the total 
number of projects under construction. Six of these were newly 
started large and medium-sized projects, three fewer than the 
previous year. 
  The investment in capital construction projects by 
state-owned units was 10.389 billion yuan, up 120 percent over 
the previous year; that in technical innovation and 
transformation projects was 4.723 billion yuan, up 61.6 percent; 
that in the construction of commodity houses was 1.72 billion 
yuan, up 300 percent; and that in others was 284 million yuan, 
up 79.9 percent. 
  There was tremendous growth and greater proportion of 
investment in tertiary industry, with the focus on key 
construction projects. Major progress was achieved in 
constructing the great passage to the sea in the southwest, and 
the growth of investment in tertiary industry -- such as 
communications and transportation -- was conspicuous. 
Investment by state-owned units in primary industry was 353 
million yuan, up 14.1 percent over the previous year, and its 
overall share dropped from the previous year's 53.3 percent to 
45.5 percent. Of this, investment in the energy industry was 
1.690 billion yuan, up 46.4 percent, and its overall share 
dropped from 14.0 percent to 9.9 percent; that in the raw and 
processed materials industry was 2.770 billion yuan, up 100 
percent, and its overall share rose from 16.2 percent to 16.5 
percent; whereas not much growth was registered in investment in 
the machinery, as well as light and textile industries, with 
their proportions falling by dropped 0.3 percent and 2.5 
percent, respectively. Investment in tertiary industry was 8.97 
billion yuan, up 150 percent over the previous year, and its 
overall share rose from the previous year's 43.0 percent to 52.4 
percent, of which investment in communications and 
transportation, as well as post and telecommunications services, 
was 2.986 billion yuan, up 150 percent over the previous year, 
and their overall share rose from 14.2 percent to 17.4 percent. 
  The pace of constructing key projects was accelerated. A 
total of 5.347 billion yuan of investment in 34 key projects 
throughout the region was completed, up 61.7 percent over the 
previous year. The 400 km-long second-grade highway between 
Nanning and Wuzhou was completed and opened to traffic on 18 
October; two no. 2 generating sets at the Yantan and 
Tianshengqiao hydropower stations were completed and put into 
operation in August and September, respectively; and the no. 3 
generating set of the power station in the shipping center of 
Guiping officially started generating power as early as in 
February. Moreover, smooth progress was made in a number of key 
construction projects, namely, the Qinzhou-Beihai Railway, the 
Guilin Liangjiang International Airport, the airports in Liuzhou 
and Wuzhou, the Guangxi Pingguo Aluminum Company, the Zhaoping 
hydropower station, and the Hexian County pulp mill in Wuzhou. 
  The major productivity (or efficiency) newly added by 
capital 
construction and transformation projects throughout the region 
was: 563,000 kw of generating capacity; 16,000 tonnes of 
machine-made paper and paperboard per year; 2.70 million tonnes 
of port handling capacity; and 2,000 km of optical fiber cables 
for long-distance communications. 
  IV. Communications, Posts and Telecommunications 
  Communications and transportation, as well as post and 
telecommunications services, registered faster growth. In 1993, 
a total of 4.633 billion yuan of added value was completed by 
these sectors, up 20.1 percent over the previous year. However, 
the fact that the development of communications and 
transportation lagged behind economic development remained an 
outstanding problem. In particular, there was a wide gap 
between supply and demand in railway transportation, and the 
potential of highway transportation had not been brought into 
full play. 
  The volume of passenger and freight transport in the 
communications sector was as follows: 


