<H5>  VI. Foreign Economic Relations </H5>
  The pace of opening up to the outside world was further 
accelerated and a new breakthrough was made in the utilization 
of foreign capital. In 1993, our region enthusiastically 
improved the hardware and software environment for investment 
and seized the favorable opportunity to successfully hold two 
trade fairs in Hong Kong, thus vigorously promoting the 
development of foreign economic relations and trade throughout 
the region. 
  Total trade volume in 1993 amounted to $2.051 billion, up 
26.3 percent over the previous year, of which the volume of 
exports was $1.325 billion, up 19.6 percent, whereas the volume 
of imports was $726 million, up 39.4 percent. Tremendous growth 
was registered in the volume of enterprise exports, with exports 
for the whole year reaching $145 million, up 31.8 percent over 
the previous year, and their share in the total volume of 
foreign trade throughout the region rose from 9.9 percent in the 
previous year to 10.9 percent. Total border trade volume was 
2.87 billion yuan, down 10.1 percent over the previous year. 
  Utilization of foreign capital increased by 100 percent. A 
total of 2,478 new agreements for utilization of foreign capital 
were signed in 1993, which was 1,140 more than signed in the 
previous year. The amount of foreign capital contracted reached 
$3.814 billion, up 163 percent, and a total of $924 million was 
actually utilized, registering an increase of 304 percent, of 
which $872 million was invested directly by foreign businessmen, 
registering growth of 380 percent -- one of the largest among 
the 12 coastal provinces and regions in the country. New 
progress was achieved in economic and technological cooperation 
inside and outside the region. In 1993, 24 construction 
projects and labor projects contracted by our region were signed 
with the outside, and the contracted amount was $109 million, up 
120 percent over the previous year. A total of 2,200 
cooperation projects were implemented, and a total of 3.8 
billion yuan of capital introduced from areas outside the region 
was available, registering an increase of 120 percent over the 
previous year. 
  As far as international tourism was concerned, the number of 
tourists received in 1993 decreased slightly. A total of 
510,920 foreigners; overseas Chinese; and compatriots from Hong 
Kong, Macao, and Taiwan; who came to Guangxi for sightseeing, 
visits, or other activities were received in 1993, down 13.4 
percent from the previous year. Income from tourism amounted to 
505 million yuan (in Foreign Exchange Certificates), down 8.4 
percent from the previous year. Since the field of operations 
was broadened and new scenic spots for tourism added, a large 
number of overseas tourists still find it attractive to visit 
our region, and we should continue to be optimistic about our 
tourism. 
<H5>  VII. Science, Education, Culture, Public Health, and Sports </H5>
  New results were scored in scientific and technological 
research and in the popularization of scientific and 
technological achievements. A total of 480 scientific and 
technological achievements were registered at and above the 
provincial and departmental levels throughout the region, of 
which 24 were internationally advanced achievements, 29 were 
pioneer works in the country, 283 were domestically advanced 
achievements, 96 were leading works in the region, 48 were 
advanced ones in the region, three were granted state awards for 
progress in science and technology, two were granted state Spark 
Awards, 186 were granted autonomous regional awards for progress 
in science and technology, and 14 were granted the autonomous 
regional Spark Awards. In 1993, a total of 5,477 patent 
applications were handled and 2,505 patents were approved. The 
market for the transfer of technology expanded further. There 
were 632 technological and trade institutions in our region 
which signed a total of 579 technological contracts in 1993, 
with the transaction amount reaching 50.669 million yuan. Key 
scientific and technological achievements scored throughout our 
region in 1993 were: Research into resection of the larynx in 
glottal cancer suffers and the reconstruction of the epiglottis; 
experimental research conducted in tree shrews for the study of 
the relationship between the Hepatitis B virus and aflatoxin in 
human bodies and the incidence of primary liver cancer; research 
into a graphic multimedia system called GBH [expansion unknown]; 
research into the cyclical movement of two-dimensional flows; 
research into Hercules' mixture [da li shen 1129 0500 4377]; and 
so on. Remarkable economic and social benefit was brought about 
by popularizing the application of some of these achievements. 
  Development zones developed steadily in the process of 
rectifying the economic order and improving the economic 
environment. In 1993, there were 18 development zones 
throughout the region, of which five were at the state level, 
while 13 were at the regional level. In addition, the 
establishment of seven development zones has not been approved 
yet. A total of 215 scientific and technological enterprises, 
which realized 797 million yuan of output value and 66.70 
million yuan of profits and taxes, have been initiated in the 
three new- and high-technology development zones in Nanning, 
Guilin, and Liuzhou. 
  Changes in the contingent of scientific and technical 
personnel were brought about by the market economy. By the end 
of 1993, state-owned units had a total of 661,200 professional 
technical personnel, registering a decrease by 7,800 from the 
previous year. 
  Further development was achieved in educational undertakings 
in the midst of reform. In 1993, a total of 248 students were 
enrolled in postgraduate courses, up 72.2 percent over the 
previous year. Institutions of higher learning took in 19,514 
new undergraduate students, up 20.6 percent, whereas secondary 
vocational and technical education developed rapidly. By the 
end of 1993, there were 352,800 students studying in various 
types of secondary vocational and technical schools (including 
45,900 students in technical worker training schools), up 190 
percent over the previous year. By the end of 1993, there were 
1.4413 million students in junior secondary schools and 6.1077 
million pupils in primary schools, up 5.4 and 2.7 percent over 
the previous year, respectively. The enrollment rate of primary 
school-age children (7-11 years of age) was 97.9 percent, 97.9 
percent of primary students did not drop out, and their rate of 
continuing studies at the secondary level rose from the previous 
year's 67.1 percent to 70.2 percent. 
  Cultural undertakings continued to develop in a healthy 
manner. By the end of 1993, there were 115 art performing 
groups; 99 libraries; 96 cultural centers; 35 museums; 4,433 
film-projection units, with 690,300 film shows and 214 million 
moviegoers; six newly produced feature films; 13 television 
stations; and 14 radio stations. In 1993, 46.75 million copies 
of newspapers, 42.66 million copies of magazines, and 31.53 
copies of 34,000 types of books were issued. 
  Public health undertakings and medical facilities further 
improved. By the end of 1993, there were 76,000 hospital beds 
in our region, up 2,700 beds or 3.7 percent over the previous 
year. There were 110,700 full-time health workers, down 2 
percent from the previous year; of whom 51,600 were doctors 
(including 39,200 senior doctors of traditional Chinese medicine 
and of Western medicine), up 3 percent; and 33,700 nurses, up 
2.1 percent. 
  New results were achieved in sports undertakings. Athletes 
of our region won 65 gold, silver, and bronze medals in the 
National Sports Meet; won eight gold medals, two silver medals, 
and three bronze medals in major international competitions; 
broke eight Asian records; and broke 15 national records. 
<H5>  VIII. Population and People's Life </H5>
  The pace of population growth was brought under control. 
According to a sample survey of population changes, the crude 
birth rate of the population was 19.6 per thousand, and the 
crude death rate was 6.4 per thousand, resulting in a natural 
growth rate of 13.2 per thousand or 0.3 percent higher than the 
figure for the previous year, but still within the limits of the 
planned target. It is estimated that the total population of our 
region was 44.38 million by the end of 1993, or an increase of 
580,000 over the figure at the end of 1992. 
  The income of residents continued to increase and their 
living conditions further improved. Data from a sample survey 
showed that the annual per capita income of urban residents that 
could be used as living expenses was 2,611 yuan in 1993, up 38.5 
percent over the previous year, or a real growth of 12.3 percent 
allowing for price rises. The per capita net income of peasants 
was 885 yuan, up 20.9 percent over the previous year, or a real 
growth of 4.3 percent, allowing for price rises. However, the 
gap in the income level between urban and rural areas widened 
and rose from 1:2.6 (peasants' income as 1) to 1:3; the living 
standard of workers and staff in some enterprises operating in 
the red declined; and peasants in poverty-stricken were still in 
straitened circumstances. 
  The employment service system and the social security system 
for retirees was gradually perfected. A total of 172,000 people 
were given jobs in cities and towns in 1993, and the urban 
unemployment rate was 3 percent by the end of the year, down 0.3 
percent from the previous year and lower than the annual 
controlled target. There was wider social insurance coverage of 
workers and staff in urban enterprises. A total of 1.425 
million workers and staff and 256,000 retirees have joined 
comprehensive social insurance programs. Moreover, the mechanism 
of enterprises' hiring workers was further perfected and the 
number of workers and staff grew more slowly than before. By 
the end of 1993, workers and staff in our region numbered 3.364 
million, up 0.7 percent over the previous year, of whom workers 
and staff of staff-owned units were 2.809 million, up 1.4 
percent, whereas individual workers in cities and towns were 
366,000, up 11.2 percent. 
  Workers and staff earned more real income and residents had 
a 
stronger sense of financial investment. In 1993, the total wage 
bill of workers and staff was 1.061 billion yuan, up 25.8 
percent over the end of 1992. The average monetary wage of 
workers and staff was 3,202 yuan, up 23.6 percent over the 
previous year, or a real increase of 0.2 percent allowing for 
price rises. With the gradual improvement of residents' living 
conditions, more and more residents made financial investments. 
Statistics showed that in 1993, there were approximately 10,000 
stock-purchasers throughout our region, and more and more 
residents purchased stocks, bonds, and other kinds of negotiable 
securities. 
  The insurance sector played a greater role in economic 
construction. Insurance premiums in 1993 totalled 146.65 
billion yuan, up 20.2 percent over the previous year, of which 
premiums for property insurance were 116.6 billion yuan. A 
total of 13,532 enterprises participated in enterprise property 
insurance programs, 4.5554 million households participated in 
household property insurance programs, and 11.53 million people 
participated in life insurance programs of various kinds. 
Insurance companies took 148,800 cases of claims for loss of 
property, and paid indemnities of 371 million yuan for settled 
cases. Another 371 million yuan was paid to 394,800 people as 
reparations in life insurance programs. 
  Urban and rural living conditions further improved. In 1993, 
a total of 2.77 million square meters of new residential 
buildings were completed in urban areas and 12.31 million square 
meters of new houses were built in rural areas. 
  Social welfare undertakings continued to develop. In 1993, 
there were 7,976 beds in social welfare institutions of various 
types in our region, with 5,636 occupants. A total of 4.693 
million people in need received various types of relief funds in 
urban and rural areas. 
Notes: (1) Data listed in the communique were annual 
statistics reported. Some figures were provided by departments. 
  (2) The gross value of GDP and various indexes of added 
value were calculated on the basis of current prices, and growth 
rates were calculated on the basis of constant prices. 
  (3) According to the State Statistical Bureau's 
stipulations, from 1992 on, the index of gross output value was 
abolished. 

